        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Yelp</strong> is a consumer review platform and local business directory launched in 2004. Users write reviews, upload photos, and rate businesses on a 5-star scale across categories including restaurants, home services, retail, and healthcare. With over 200 million reviews and direct integrations with Apple Maps and Amazon Alexa, Yelp is one of the most influential review platforms for local businesses in the United States.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Yelp for Business</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">8 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local business owners think of Yelp as just a review site. But Yelp data powers Apple Maps' business reviews, Bing's local results in some categories, and Amazon Alexa's responses to "find me a [service] near me" queries. Your Yelp presence has a reach far beyond yelp.com itself.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Yelp?</h2>
        <p>Yelp was founded in 2004 by Jeremy Stoppelman and Russel Simmons, both former PayPal employees. The platform launched in San Francisco and quickly grew into the dominant review platform for US local businesses — particularly in cities and consumer-facing service categories.</p>
        <p>The platform works on a crowd-sourced model. Any registered Yelp user can write a review, attach photos, and rate a business from 1 to 5 stars. Unlike Google Reviews, which are associated with Google accounts, Yelp has its own reputation system — "Yelpers" build community standing through Elite status, review counts, and engagement on the platform.</p>
        <p>As of 2026, Yelp reports approximately 73 million unique monthly visitors in the US and hosts over 200 million cumulative reviews. The categories with the highest review volume are restaurants, bars, nightlife, and home services.</p>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Yelp works for businesses</h2>
        <p>Business listings on Yelp are created by Yelp's data team or automatically from business registration data — meaning your business may already have a Yelp page even if you've never created one. Claiming your listing through Yelp for Business (biz.yelp.com) is the essential first step.</p>
        <h3>Yelp listing components</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Business name, address, and phone</strong> — your NAP (Name, Address, Phone) data</li>
          <li><strong>Business categories</strong> — you can select up to 3</li>
          <li><strong>Hours of operation</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Photos</strong> — uploaded by the business and by reviewers</li>
          <li><strong>Attributes</strong> — accessibility features, payment types, health and safety, specialties</li>
          <li><strong>Services offered</strong> — specific service menu items</li>
          <li><strong>Website URL and social links</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Reviews and star rating</strong> — the most prominent feature</li>
        </ul>
        <h3>Yelp's review filter</h3>
        <p>Yelp is unique among review platforms for its automated "review filter" — a system that hides reviews it suspects are fake, incentivised, or from low-credibility accounts. Filtered reviews don't count toward your star rating or total review count. This is a controversial feature: legitimate reviews from real customers are often filtered if the reviewer is new to Yelp or hasn't established platform activity.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why Yelp matters beyond Yelp.com</div>
          <p>Apple Maps uses Yelp as its primary review source for US businesses. Amazon Alexa answers local business queries using Yelp data. Bing Local also surfaces Yelp ratings in some categories. A strong Yelp presence reaches users who have never opened the Yelp app.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="ranking">How Yelp ranks businesses in search results</h2>
        <p>When a user searches Yelp for "plumber near me" or "best Italian restaurant downtown," Yelp's algorithm determines which businesses appear and in what order. The three primary ranking factors are:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Relevance.</strong> How closely does the business match the search query? This includes category match, keyword presence in your business description, and the text of your reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Distance.</strong> How close is the business to the user's location? Yelp heavily weights proximity — a closer business with fewer reviews will often outrank a highly-rated business across town.</li>
          <li><strong>Reputation.</strong> Your overall star rating, total review count (only non-filtered reviews count), recency of reviews, and whether you have photos all contribute to your reputation score.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Beyond these three, Yelp's algorithm also considers profile completeness. Businesses with all fields filled out, multiple photos, and active Yelp interaction (responding to reviews) tend to rank better than equivalent businesses with sparse profiles.</p>

        <h2 id="yelp-vs-google">Yelp vs. Google Reviews for local businesses</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Yelp</th><th>Google Reviews</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Direct SEO impact</strong></td>
                <td>Minimal (Yelp pages rank in Google)</td>
                <td>Direct Google ranking signal</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Apple Maps integration</strong></td><td>Primary review source</td><td>Not used</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Review filter</strong></td><td>Aggressive automated filter</td><td>Less aggressive, manual removal</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Reviewer identity</strong></td><td>Yelp account with history</td><td>Google account</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Ad platform</strong></td><td>Yelp Ads (CPC)</td><td>Google Ads / Local Service Ads</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Best for</strong></td><td>Restaurants, home services, health</td><td>All local business categories</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for Yelp in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Claim your listing.</strong> Go to biz.yelp.com and claim your free business page. Complete every field — business hours, specialties, service offerings, website URL, and photos. Unclaimed listings show a "Claim This Business" banner that erodes consumer trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Upload high-quality photos.</strong> Businesses with more photos rank better on Yelp. Upload at least 10 professional photos covering your location, products, services, and team. Owner-uploaded photos display with a crown icon, signalling credibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Respond to positive reviews with a thank-you, and respond to negative reviews with an empathetic, solutions-focused reply. Never argue or dismiss complaints publicly — it signals poor customer service to prospective customers reading the exchange.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep your NAP consistent.</strong> Your business name, address, and phone number on Yelp should match exactly what appears on your Google Business Profile, website, and other directories. Inconsistent NAP data creates citation confusion that hurts local SEO.</li>
          <li><strong>Encourage organic reviews — carefully.</strong> Yelp prohibits asking customers to write Yelp reviews. You can let customers know you're on Yelp (stickers, website badges) but cannot solicit reviews. Doing so can trigger the filter against even genuine reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Use Yelp Check-in Offers.</strong> Yelp allows businesses to offer discounts to customers who check in. This drives engagement and can boost your listing's activity signals.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor your listing for spam.</strong> Competitors or disgruntled former employees sometimes post fake negative reviews. Report any review that violates Yelp's content guidelines promptly.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Yelp mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Asking customers for Yelp reviews.</strong> This is explicitly against Yelp's terms of service. It can get legitimate reviews filtered and can result in a consumer alert badge on your listing warning that you have been caught soliciting reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews.</strong> Unanswered negative reviews signal that you don't care about customer feedback. A thoughtful response — even to an unfair review — demonstrates professionalism to prospective customers.</li>
          <li><strong>Leaving your listing unclaimed.</strong> An unclaimed listing gives you no ability to respond to reviews, update inaccurate information, or prevent a competitor from advertising on your page (Yelp shows competitor ads on unclaimed business pages).</li>
          <li><strong>Inconsistent business information.</strong> Different phone numbers or addresses across Yelp, Google, and your website create citation inconsistency — a well-documented local ranking problem.</li>
          <li><strong>Expecting reviews to stay visible.</strong> Yelp's filter is aggressive. If customers you ask (informally or directly) write reviews, and those reviewers are new Yelpers, the reviews will likely be filtered. Focus on providing an excellent experience and let reviews come naturally.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does Yelp affect Google rankings?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Not directly — Yelp reviews don't transfer to Google. However, Yelp pages often rank in Google's organic results for local business searches, and Yelp powers reviews on Apple Maps and some Bing local results, making your Yelp presence indirectly important for overall local visibility.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Why does Yelp hide some reviews?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yelp's automated review filter removes reviews it suspects are fake, incentivised, or from users without established Yelp history. Reviews from new accounts, users with no profile photo, or only one review on their account are most likely to be filtered. Soliciting reviews can trigger the filter for legitimate reviews too.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I remove negative Yelp reviews?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>You cannot remove a negative review simply because you disagree with it. You can report a review to Yelp if it violates their content guidelines (contains personal attacks, is clearly fraudulent, or is not about a genuine customer experience). Yelp will review the report and may remove it if it violates policy.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is Yelp advertising worth it for local businesses?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>It depends on your category and location. Yelp ads work well for high-search categories like restaurants, plumbers, dentists, and auto repair. For niche B2B services or rural locations, the ROI is often lower. Test with a monthly budget before committing to a long-term contract.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How does Yelp rank businesses in search results?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yelp's search ranking is based on relevance (how well your business matches the search query and category), distance from the searcher, and reputation signals — primarily your star rating, number of reviews, and recency of reviews. Businesses with complete profiles and active photo uploads also tend to rank better.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

